post_text:
Returning/Picking Up Items at the MS/HS Entrance

Student belongings as well as artwork and 3rd Quarter Academic Awards will be available for pick up on May 18th - 20th at the MS/HS entrance. At the same time, we need students to return their candy bar money, band instruments, library books, textbooks, and if all online work is complete, their Chromebooks (including the Chromebook case/bag and charger).

Here is the drop-off/pick up schedule for the middle school. Please use the MS/HS entrance and have one parent or one student per family enter at a time.

Monday, May 18th Grades 5 & 7
10:00 am-Noon or 3:00 pm-5:00 pm

Tuesday, May 19th Grade 6
10:00 am-Noon or 3:00 pm-5:00 pm

Wednesday, May 20th Grade 8

text:
Returning/Picking Up Items at the MS/HS Entrance

Student belongings as well as artwork and 3rd Quarter Academic Awards will be available for pick up on May 18th - 20th at the MS/HS entrance. At the same time, we need students to return their candy bar money, band instruments, library books, textbooks, and if all online work is complete, their Chromebooks (including the Chromebook case/bag and charger).

Here is the drop-off/pick up schedule for the middle school. Please use the MS/HS entrance and have one parent or one student per family enter at a time.

Monday, May 18th Grades 5 & 7
10:00 am-Noon or 3:00 pm-5:00 pm

Tuesday, May 19th Grade 6
10:00 am-Noon or 3:00 pm-5:00 pm

Wednesday, May 20th Grade 8
10:00 am-Noon or 3:00 pm-5:00 pm

Please call the middle school and arrange another time for drop off if your child needs their computer beyond the scheduled day to return items.
Thank you.

post_text: Buckeye Central Schools parents and students... As you know by now, Governor DeWine closed Ohio schools for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year this past Monday. Since his announcement (and even before), we have been working diligently to address the many end-of-the-year topics that must be handled. We will be sharing information regarding graduation, finalizing school work, locker clean out, Chromebooks and all other pertinent year-end information within the next couple of weeks. Be assured that we are working hard on plans to conduct a memorable graduation ceremony for our Seniors 2020. Thank you for your patience and support during these challenging and unprecedented times. The minute we are able to finalize our plans, you will be the first to know! :-) Stay healthy and safe. BC_Strong!

EARTH DAY turns 50 today!! Take a look at my website for some ideas on how to celebrate!
- upcycling plastic bags
- litter pick-up BINGO and scavenger hunt
- upcycling to make your own planters

https://sites.google.com/bcbucks.org/bcsteam-mrscaudill

It might be time to remind students of some good habits:
1. Unplug items that are fully charged (Chromebooks) or not in use (like your toaster oven);
2. Turn off water when scrubbing hands, brushing teeth, washing face/body, etc.;
3. Turn off lights when not in a room and when it is daytime;
4. Get out and pick up the trash in our yards, ditches, fence rows, etc.;
5. Use big appliances during off peak hours (those times should be posted on your electric company's website)
6. My favorite: Use your clothes lines or racks to dry your laundry outside!

BUCKEYE CENTRAL TO OFFER MEALS

Buckeye Central will be providing meals to students during the closure of school due to the Coronavirus. Beginning Wednesday, March 18, brown-bagged breakfast and lunch will be available to any student that needs it.
Meals will be available weekdays between 11:30 a.m.- 12:30p.m. at the following sites:
Bloomville Community Center
Tiro Fire Department
Chatfield Fire Department
St. John’s Lutheran Church - New Washington
No payment for meals will be expected or collected. For tracking purposes, the name of each student will be recorded.
It is important that you respond to the One Call message that you will receive on Monday evening so that an adequate number of meals can be prepared.

BUCYRUS — Buckeye Central got its revenge against Bucyrus on Feb. 15 in boys basketball for a loss earlier in the season, and one player nearly doubled his per-game averages to help push the Bucks to a 71-44 win.
Sophomore guard Aiden McDougal totaled 11 points and five rebounds, nearly double his per-game scoring average of 6.4 points per game and greater than his 3.9 rebounds per game.
McDougal also excelled at the defensive end, finishing the game with three steals, well above his 0.7 steals-per-game average.
Congratulations to Aiden McDougal of Buckeye Central, the Spitzer Motors Game Changer for Feb. 15!

post_text:
Jesse Weinberger brought her internet safety message to Buckeye Central this week. In between touches of humor, she asked students not to be like sheep and warned them how dangerous Snapchat and TikTok could be for them, how livestreaming anything (except maybe gaming) is a bad idea, and how online users hide behind fake identities more than we realize.

She made it clear that under the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act, social media use for children younger than 13 years of age is illegal.

Parents, grandparents, guardians, and extended family members, if you want to learn more, she will be back for a special presentation just for you on Wednesday, February 19th at 7:00 pm in the Buckeye Central Multipurpose Room.
text:
Jesse Weinberger brought her internet safety message to Buckeye Central this week. In between touches of humor, she asked students not to be like sheep and warned them how dangerous Snapchat and TikTok could be for them, how livestreaming anything (except maybe gaming) is a bad idea, and how online users hide behind fake identities more than we realize.

She made it clear that under the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act, social media use for children younger than 13 years of age is illegal.

Parents, grandparents, guardians, and extended family members, if you want to learn more, she will be back for a special presentation just for you on Wednesday, February 19th at 7:00 pm in the Buckeye Central Multipurpose Room.

post_text:
Buckeye Central’s eSports team will participate in the Ohio eSports League STATE CHAMPIONSHIP on Saturday, November 23 at Tiffin University!!! BC’s esports team went undefeated in the regular season with a record of 7-0 (Cardinal Conference Champs!) which qualified them to compete in the championship on Saturday! The final four teams in Ohio include BC along with Shaker Heights, Bluffton, and Chillicothe. We will play Bluffton in the semi-final game. The winner advances to the final game competing against the winner of Shaker Heights and Chillicothe. You can view the live stream of this competition using these sites:
https://www.twitch.tv/esports_ohio
https://bit.ly/esoyoutube

BC’s team plays the game, Overwatch.

For a schedule go to Ohio’s eSports League website:
http://esportsohio.org

GOOD LUCK to our eSports team!!!

post_text:
America's Fun Fitness Coach visited BC today. Jim Steffen asked our students to exercise, eat healthy foods, and have confidence in themselves. Using Coach Al Baker's words, Mr. Steffen reminded students to grit their teeth, dig in, and employ the Big O--optimism! He stressed that encouraging one another strengthens the supporter and the person they cheer. Across two forty-five-minute presentations, Jim showed his unbelievable strength, balance, and determination.

A big thank you to Mr. Robinett for coordinating the event and to the Endowment Fund members for covering the costs.

shared_text:
Sagebrush Artistry added 11 new photos to the album: Buckeye Central Local Schools Cafeteria Mural — at Buckeye Central High School.
August 11, 2019 at 10:53 PM · New Washington, OH ·

Another great experience painting for Buckeye Central Local Schools in New Washington, OH. This very large mural is painted in the cafeteria and also doubles as the common area to gather before and after sporting events. The "Buck Stop" is the concession stand during sporting events. 9 Sports = 1 Team is a very important reminder of what the school is all about. #WeR_BC is commonly used by the administrators, teachers & students. Each graphic measures 30" x 30". The second pic with the red wall is the "before" pic. I have painted for this school district several times now...and have appreciated each and every experience. Very classy environment where students come first!
